burst-multiplier: 1` to keep burst at 2. But even with burst=2, if tokens are being added at the same rate they're consumed, requests might still succeed. The safest approach is to set `limit-rps: 1` with a small burst, which would cause roughly half the requests to get 429s when sent at 2 RPS. The burst size is what allows requests above the sustained rate, so with a 2 RPS limit and burst of 2, the test sending at exactly 2 RPS would consume the burst initially but then stay within the rate limit without hitting 429s. I need to either lower the rate to 1 RPS with a burst of 2, or reconsider the configuration to actually trigger rate limiting in the test. Let me examine the nginx ingress annotations more closely to understand how the burst multiplier translates to actual burst capacity. So with a 1 RPS limit and burst of 1, sending 10 requests at roughly 2 RPS should reliably trigger 429s on the excess requests. Let me go with that configuration instead. I'm realizing I might be misunderstanding the setup—there's only 1 pod running despite the deployment specifying 3 replicas, so I should probably scale it up first. But even with 3 replicas, the round-robin distribution would spread the 2 RPS across them, meaning each replica only handles about 0.67 RPS, which wouldn't trigger a 1 RPS limit. I need to think about whether the rate limiting should be global across all replicas rather than per-replica, or maybe I should use connection limits instead. Below 2 RPS to trigger 429s during the test. I'm weighing two approaches: setting the limit to exactly 2 RPS with no burst multiplier (so the first couple requests get through but subsequent ones hit the limit), or setting it to 1 RPS with a burst of 2 to allow an initial burst but then enforce stricter rate limiting.\n\nI'm leaning toward `limit-rps: 2` with `limit-burst-multiplier: 1` since it creates a scenario where the burst is quickly consumed and then the rate limiting kicks in as requests arrive at 2 per second. Let me work through the exact mechanics of how Nginx's leaky bucket algorithm evaluates whether to reject a request based on the excess tokens and refill rate.\n\nWhen I test this with requests arriving at exactly the rate limit, they all get accepted because the excess tokens refill at the same pace they're consumed. The 429 errors only trigger when clients send faster than the configured limit. If I drop the rate to 1 RPS, the default burst of 5 means all 10 requests would pass through, so I'd need to pair it with `limit-burst-multiplier: 1` to actually see rejections.\n\nWith rate=1/s and burst=1, the math shows the second request at t=0.5 would exceed the burst capacity and get rejected, then subsequent requests keep hitting 429s. That's too strict for what I'm trying to test. The real challenge is that the test loop with 0.5s sleep between requests might not translate to exactly 2 requests per second in practice—the actual timing depends on network latency and how long each curl takes to complete.\n\nIf I set limit-rps to 2 with a burst multiplier of 1, the steady-state rate matches the test's approximate send rate, so I might not see any 429s reliably. But with 3 replicas and round-robin load balancing, each replica only sees every third request from a single client, which further reduces the effective rate hitting any one replica. So even with limit-rps: 1 per replica, the distributed requests might stay under the limit.\n\nI need to think about this differently—maybe the configuration needs to be more aggressive, or I'm misunderstanding how the load balancing interacts with the rate limiting.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1746,"cache_read_input_tokens":30201,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1746},"output_tokens":41,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":nul