tes based on how far ahead we are of the rate limit, and only rejects when it exceeds the burst capacity.\n\nSince requests arriving at exactly the rate limit replenish tokens perfectly, I need to either increase the request rate above 2 RPS or lower the rate limit itself to actually trigger rejections in the test. Actually, I'm realizing the test might be sending faster than 2 RPS because the curl command itself takes time—if curl takes a few milliseconds and sleep is 0.5s, the actual rate could be closer to 2 RPS or slightly above. And if the sleep timer isn't perfectly precise on the system, it could drift even faster, which would trigger some 429s with a strict rate limit.\n\nBut even at 2.02 RPS with a burst of 2, the excess only accumulates by 0.01 per request, so it would take 200 requests to exceed the burst—way more than the 10 requests in the test. I'm hitting a wall here. Let me reconsider what the actual problem might be.\n\nMaybe the setup involves 3 replicas and the test is designed to send requests at a rate exceeding 2 RPS per replica, or perhaps the rate limit is distributed differently across replicas. Or maybe I need to look at what the test case definition actually expects to happen at this stage.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":487,"cache_read_input_tokens":39752,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":487},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"78397064-0ad2-4638-a19c-c06350a9d4be","uuid":"b1fa0e6c-86d3-4925-815c-58f05a10446a","request_id":"req_011CcLDkC9be3Eqa9iMYXDdB"}
